const EVENTS = [
  // ---- The Ancients ----
  { era:"The Ancients", entry:"Ancient Past", yr:"~2000 yrs ago", title:"The Calamity Falls", art:"calamity",
    blurb:"A lifeform from beyond the stars — later named Jenova — crashes into the Planet. It infects and mimics the Cetra, the gentle 'Ancients' who could hear the Planet's voice, nearly driving them extinct. Survivors seal the Calamity away in the far north.",
    detail:"Jenova did not conquer the Cetra with armies — it spread like a disease. It could take the shape of loved ones, whisper in familiar voices, and infect entire migrations of the Ancients, turning them into monsters or hollow puppets. The few uninfected Cetra hunted it down at terrible cost and sealed it in the northern snows. The Planet, wounded by the impact, also produced its first WEAPONs in response. Shinra would later excavate Jenova's body from that 2,000-year-old stratum and, fatally, mistake it for one of the very Ancients it had slaughtered." },
  { era:"The Ancients", entry:"Ancient Past", yr:"long ago", title:"The Cetra's Promise", art:"cetra",
    blurb:"The dwindling Cetra dream of the Promised Land — a place of supreme peace and abundant Mako. Their bloodline thins until almost none remain to keep the old covenant with the Planet.",
    detail:"The Cetra were a migratory people who never settled, travelling the world to nurture it and converse with the Planet, trusting that their journey would one day end in the Promised Land. Most surviving Cetra eventually abandoned the hard travelling life to settle as ordinary humans — diluting the bloodline until 'the Ancients' became myth. By the present day only Ifalna and her daughter Aerith remain to truly hear the Planet, which is exactly why Shinra and Sephiroth both hunt the Promised Land through her." },

  // ---- Rise of Shinra ----
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Shinra Era", yr:"decades past", title:"Shinra Bleeds the Planet", art:"reactor",
    blurb:"The Shinra Electric Power Company pivots from a weapons maker to a Mako energy monopoly. By draining refined Lifestream as fuel, it builds the towering metropolis of Midgar — and quietly kills the world to power it.",
    detail:"Mako reactors don't gather energy — they puncture the Planet and siphon the Lifestream directly, like needles in a vein. The convenience is intoxicating and the cost invisible, so the world looks the other way while the land around each reactor slowly dies. Midgar, eight reactors arranged around a central tower, becomes the symbol of it all: the wealthy live on an elevated plate while the poor are crushed in the slums beneath, in perpetual shadow. Shinra is not merely a company but the de facto world government, with its own army, science division, and secret police." },
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Shinra Era", yr:"~10 yrs of war", title:"The Wutai War", art:"war",
    blurb:"Shinra's military crushes the proud eastern nation of Wutai, stripping it of its independence, its pride, and its Materia. The campaign forges the Turks and SOLDIER into legends — and leaves a young Yuffie burning for her homeland's glory.",
    detail:"Wutai was the last nation to resist Shinra's global expansion, and the only one with a rival spiritual tradition built around Materia rather than Mako reactors. Its defeat made battlefield legends of SOLDIERs like Sephiroth and gave the Turks their reputation. For Wutai it meant humiliation: reduced to a tourist resort town, its warrior culture gutted. Yuffie's entire arc — stealing Materia to rebuild Wutai's strength — is the long aftershock of this war." },
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Shinra Era", yr:"~30 yrs ago", title:"The Jenova Project", spoiler:true, art:"lab",
    blurb:"Believing Jenova to be a Cetra, Shinra launches the Jenova Project. Hojo and Lucrecia bear a child injected with Jenova's cells before birth: Sephiroth — engineered to be the perfect SOLDIER. Hollander's rival Project G creates Genesis and Angeal.",
    detail:"Project S (Sephiroth) injected Jenova's cells into a fetus, gambling that a human grown with the 'Ancient's' power could lead Shinra to the Promised Land. In parallel, Hollander's Project G used cells from Angeal's mother, Gillian, to create Genesis and Angeal. The fatal irony underpins everything: Jenova was never a Cetra at all, so every 'Ancient' power Shinra engineered is really the calamity that murdered the Cetra, now wearing a human face." },
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Shinra Era", yr:"~30 yrs ago", title:"Gast's Defection", spoiler:true, art:"reels",
    blurb:"Professor Gast, the Jenova Project's founder, realizes Jenova is no Cetra but the Calamity itself — and flees Shinra in horror. He weds the true last Cetra, Ifalna, and they have a daughter, Aerith. Hojo hunts Gast down and murders him to seize the family.",
    detail:"Gast was Shinra's most brilliant mind and the one who first misidentified Jenova — the original sin of the whole saga. When he understood his error, he abandoned the project and disappeared with Ifalna, the genuine Cetra he had grown to love, hoping to study the Ancients honestly and raise their daughter in peace. His ambitious subordinate Hojo found them, killed Gast on sight, and seized Ifalna and infant Aerith as specimens. The interviews Gast filmed with Ifalna survive as the optional 'Gast Reports.'" },
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Shinra Era", yr:"~23 yrs ago", title:"Aerith's Escape", spoiler:true, art:"station",
    blurb:"After years as Hojo's specimens, Ifalna breaks out of the Shinra labs with young Aerith. She dies on the platform of the Midgar station — and the kindly Elmyra takes the orphaned Cetra in as her own.",
    detail:"Ifalna endured roughly seven years of captivity and experimentation before escaping with her daughter. Already dying, she made it only as far as the Sector 7 train platform, where she pressed Aerith into the care of a stranger — Elmyra, who had come to the station daily to wait for a husband lost to Shinra's wars and who never came home. Elmyra raised Aerith never fully understanding what her daughter was, only that Shinra wanted her badly." },
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Shinra Era", yr:"~27 yrs ago", title:"Vincent's Sin", spoiler:true, art:"coffin",
    blurb:"The Turk Vincent Valentine, unable to stop Lucrecia, is shot by Hojo and remade through cruel experiments — left near-immortal and entombed in a coffin beneath the Shinra Manor to sleep off his guilt.",
    detail:"Vincent was assigned to protect the Jenova Project's scientists and fell in love with Lucrecia. When she chose to carry Hojo's experimental child, Vincent's failure to stop her — and his belief that he let her doom herself — became a guilt he decided he deserved to suffer forever. Hojo shot him, experimented on his body, and the resulting creature could not die. Vincent sealed himself in a coffin in the Manor basement, choosing endless sleep as penance, until the party wakes him decades later." },
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Ever Crisis", yr:"~15 yrs before", title:"The First SOLDIERs", art:"war",
    blurb:"As Shinra forges its SOLDIER program, three prototype 'P0' SOLDIERs — Glenn Lodbrok, Lucia Lin, and Matt Winsord — are sent to the remote Rhadore Archipelago to scout a site for a new Mako reactor. Ever Crisis's original arc, 'The First Soldier,' begins here.",
    detail:"When the islands' natives ambush the unit, a young Sephiroth — not yet the legend, still unused to fighting beside anyone — is forced to work as part of the team. Grudgingly, he opens up to the trio and, for a moment, finds something like friendship: a rare glimpse of the man before the monster. 'The First Soldier' fills in the dawn of SOLDIER and threads connections that surface as late as Rebirth, where Glenn reappears." },
  { era:"Rise of Shinra", entry:"Before Crisis", yr:"~15 yrs ago", title:"The Fall of Corel", art:"fire",
    blurb:"A Mako reactor accident gives Shinra a pretext to burn the coal town of Corel to the ground. Barret and his friend Dyne lose everything; Barret raises Dyne's daughter Marlene and swears vengeance on the company.",
    detail:"Barret, believing Mako would modernize his coal town, personally convinced Corel to accept a Shinra reactor. When the reactor was sabotaged, Shinra blamed the townsfolk and razed Corel, killing Barret's wife Myrna and Dyne's wife Eleanor. Barret and Dyne, fleeing across a trestle, were both shot and lost their right hands in the fall — the shared wound that turns them into mirror images. Barret took Dyne's infant daughter Marlene and a gun-arm, and carried the guilt of having invited Shinra in himself." },

  // ---- The SOLDIER Tragedy ----
  { era:"The SOLDIER Tragedy", entry:"Before Crisis", yr:"~6 yrs before", title:"AVALANCHE vs. the Turks", art:"avalanche",
    blurb:"The original AVALANCHE — led by Elfé and the fanatic Fuhito — wages a shadow war against Shinra. Veld's Turks are sent to counter them, the events chronicled in Before Crisis.",
    detail:"The first AVALANCHE was larger and more zealous than Barret's later cell, led by a charismatic radical named Elfé and willing to use far harsher methods to stop Shinra's reactors. Before Crisis follows the Turks tasked with hunting them — humanizing the 'villains' and revealing how tangled Shinra's internal politics already were. The conflict sets the template for the war the main game inherits." },
  { era:"The SOLDIER Tragedy", entry:"Crisis Core", yr:"~5 yrs before", title:"Project G & the Degradation", spoiler:true, art:"wing",
    blurb:"Hollander's Project G births Genesis and Angeal from Jenova-derived cells — but the experiment is flawed. The 'degradation' that will unravel both men, body and mind, is sown from birth, and Hollander dangles a false cure to turn Genesis against Shinra.",
    detail:"'Degradation' is the slow breakdown of a Project G subject's cells: their bodies grey, crack, and mutate, sprouting feathers and monstrous limbs while their minds fray. Genesis, learning he is essentially a defective prototype with an expiration date, is consumed by terror and envy of the 'perfect' Sephiroth. Hollander exploits this, promising a cure that requires Genesis to turn traitor — lighting the fuse on the entire SOLDIER tragedy." },
  { era:"The SOLDIER Tragedy", entry:"Crisis Core", yr:"~5 yrs before", title:"Genesis Deserts", spoiler:true, art:"wing",
    blurb:"His body degrading, SOLDIER 1st Genesis abandons Shinra and floods the world with copies of himself. His friend Angeal follows him into ruin — and forces Zack to end his life, passing on the Buster Sword.",
    detail:"Genesis mass-produces 'Genesis copies' — degraded duplicates — and wages a private war on Shinra in search of a cure. Angeal, discovering he too is an experiment and beginning to mutate, cannot bear to become a monster; he provokes his own student Zack into killing him, handing down the Buster Sword and the creed 'protect your honor and your dreams.' Both deaths shape the man Zack becomes — and, through Zack, the man Cloud pretends to be." },
  { era:"The SOLDIER Tragedy", entry:"Crisis Core", yr:"~5 yrs before", title:"Zack & the Flower Girl", art:"flower",
    blurb:"Chasing Genesis copies through the slums, the young SOLDIER Zack crashes through a ruined church roof and lands among Aerith's flowers. Amid the chaos, a tender first romance blossoms between them.",
    detail:"Zack literally falls into Aerith's life — through the roof of the abandoned Sector 5 church, into the only flowers growing anywhere in Midgar. Their brief, sweet romance (87 unsent letters later) is the emotional heart of Crisis Core. It's also why, when Aerith later meets Cloud — who carries Zack's mannerisms and memories — she feels she already knows him, an ache neither of them fully understands." },

  // ---- The Nibelheim Incident ----
  { era:"The Nibelheim Incident", entry:"Crisis Core", yr:"5 yrs before", title:"Return to Nibelheim", art:"fire",
    blurb:"Sephiroth, Zack, and a young infantryman named Cloud are sent to investigate a malfunctioning Mako reactor in the mountain village of Nibelheim — Cloud and Tifa's hometown.",
    detail:"The mission seems routine, but it places Sephiroth — already unsettled by Genesis's questions about their origins — at the doorstep of the place where he was made. One of the two helmeted infantry escorts is Cloud, who hides his face the entire time out of shame at never making SOLDIER, so neither Tifa nor anyone else recognizes him. Inside the reactor's pods, Sephiroth sees rows of mutated, Mako-deformed humans labeled as failed experiments — and the name 'Jenova' on the chamber door." },
  { era:"The Nibelheim Incident", entry:"FFVII", yr:"5 yrs before", title:"Nibelheim Burns", spoiler:true, art:"fire",
    blurb:"In the Shinra Manor library, Sephiroth reads of his origin and breaks. Declaring himself Jenova's son and the Planet's heir, he sets the village ablaze and descends to the reactor — where Cloud impales him after he strikes down Tifa and Zack.",
    detail:"Sephiroth locks himself in the Manor basement for days, devouring Gast's and Hojo's research, and emerges convinced he is the last 'Ancient,' betrayed by the humans who stole the Planet from his kind. He torches Nibelheim, cutting down anyone who flees, and marches to the reactor to claim 'Mother' — Jenova. He defeats both Zack and Sephiroth-worshipping Tifa, but the lowly grunt Cloud — enraged at the sight of the wounded Tifa — runs Sephiroth through with his own sword and hurls him into the Mako below. It is the single act of heroism Cloud's broken mind will later spend years trying to claim as Zack's, or as his own." },
  { era:"The Nibelheim Incident", entry:"FFVII", yr:"5 yrs before", title:"Zangan's Rescue", spoiler:true, art:"fire",
    blurb:"Amid the flames, the wandering martial artist Zangan carries the gravely wounded Tifa from the burning manor to safety — the same night Cloud and Zack fall into Hojo's hands.",
    detail:"Tifa is left dying at the reactor, slashed by Sephiroth's blade. Her travelling master Zangan finds her and carries her down the mountain to be treated, then quietly moves on — a small mercy in a night of horror, recorded only in an easily missed letter. Shinra's clean-up crew, meanwhile, rebuilds Nibelheim from scratch and staffs it with paid actors to erase any record of the massacre, so that when Cloud returns years later the town gaslights its own history." },
  { era:"The Nibelheim Incident", entry:"Crisis Core", yr:"5 yrs before", title:"Specimens", spoiler:true, art:"lab",
    blurb:"Hojo seizes the wounded Cloud and Zack as Jenova-cell test subjects, imprisoning them in tanks for years. Flooded with Mako, Cloud's mind begins to dissolve.",
    detail:"Hojo subjects both men to the same Jenova-reunion experiment that produced Sephiroth, sealing them in Mako tanks for roughly four years. Zack, a true SOLDIER, resists the process; Cloud, an ordinary trooper, succumbs to severe Mako poisoning that leaves him catatonic and erases the boundaries of his own memory — priming the identity collapse to come. The shared cells are why Cloud, like the Genesis copies, can later be controlled by Sephiroth's will." },
  { era:"The Nibelheim Incident", entry:"Crisis Core", yr:"~1 yr before", title:"Zack's Last Stand", spoiler:true, art:"sword",
    blurb:"Zack escapes, hauling the comatose Cloud across the wastes toward Midgar. Cornered by an army, he falls in a hail of gunfire — bequeathing his sword, his dreams, and his very identity to Cloud, who staggers on alone.",
    detail:"Branded traitors, Zack and the limp Cloud flee Hojo's lab and spend months on the run toward Midgar, where Zack dreams of becoming a mercenary. On the cliffs overlooking the city, Shinra's army finally corners them; Zack fights off hundreds before three soldiers gun him down. With his last breath he gives Cloud the Buster Sword and names him his 'living legacy.' The grief-stricken, Mako-addled Cloud — reaching for a self to hold onto — absorbs Zack's memories and persona, and walks into Midgar believing he is the SOLDIER hero his friend actually was." },

  // ---- FFVII · Meteorfall ----
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"The Bombing of Mako Reactor 1", art:"reactor",
    blurb:"In Midgar, the mercenary Cloud is hired by Barret's AVALANCHE — Jessie, Biggs, and Wedge among them — to bomb a Mako reactor. The strike against Shinra ignites the events that will decide the Planet's fate, and reunites Cloud with Tifa.",
    detail:"The game opens mid-operation: a tight, claustrophobic raid that establishes Cloud as a detached merc 'just here for the money' and AVALANCHE as scrappy idealists. The bombing's huge civilian death toll — and the question of how much of it is really Shinra's doing versus AVALANCHE's — sits at the moral center of the opening hours. It's also where Cloud first hears Sephiroth's name spoken as though he should be long dead." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"Remake / Rebirth", yr:"Year 0", title:"Whispers of Fate", spoiler:true, art:"whisper",
    blurb:"In the Remake retelling, ghostly Whispers enforce destiny itself, steering events back toward their 'known' course. The party tears through them at Midgar's edge — a defiance that fractures fate and lets the timeline diverge.",
    detail:"The Whispers (Arbiters of Fate) are the Remake trilogy's boldest invention: spectral guardians that exist to keep events on the rails of the original 1997 story, nudging characters back whenever they stray. Defeating them at the end of Remake is a literal break with destiny — a meta-statement that this retelling may not end the way longtime fans expect, and that even Sephiroth may be fighting to change his own fate." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"The Sector 7 Plate Falls", spoiler:true, art:"plate",
    blurb:"To crush AVALANCHE, Shinra drops the colossal Sector 7 plate onto the slums below, killing thousands — Biggs, Wedge, and Jessie give their lives. The party survives, but Shinra captures Aerith, the last Cetra they hope will reveal the Promised Land.",
    detail:"Heidegger's forces sever the support pillar and let an entire city plate crash down on the slum beneath, murdering tens of thousands to eliminate one resistance cell — and pin the blame on AVALANCHE. Jessie, Biggs, and Wedge die holding the pillar. Reeling, the survivors learn Shinra has taken Aerith, whom the company has watched her whole life as the key to the Promised Land. The atrocity transforms AVALANCHE's war from sabotage into something far more personal." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"A President Slain", spoiler:true, art:"masamune",
    blurb:"Escaping Shinra HQ, the party finds President Shinra impaled by the Masamune. Sephiroth — thought dead for five years — walks again. The icy Rufus Shinra inherits the company.",
    detail:"After a daring infiltration of Shinra HQ (and the discovery of the captive Jenova specimen), the party finds the President dead at his desk, the Masamune through his back and a trail leading to the Jenova chamber, now empty. The message is unmistakable: Sephiroth is alive. His son Rufus assumes control and reframes Shinra's rule around fear, while Cloud's party flees Midgar to chase a ghost across the Planet." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"The Kalm Flashback", spoiler:true, art:"memory",
    blurb:"In Kalm, Cloud recounts the Nibelheim Incident as he remembers it — casting himself as the SOLDIER hero at Sephiroth's side. The truth, buried in his shattered mind, is not what he tells.",
    detail:"Cloud narrates Nibelheim to the party as though he were the SOLDIER 1st who accompanied Sephiroth — confident, capable, present at every key moment. The retelling is vivid and convincing, and the player experiences it as fact. Only much later does it become clear the 'SOLDIER' in the story was Zack, and that Cloud has unconsciously written himself into a role he never held. The Kalm flashback is the game quietly lying to you, in-character, long before the twist." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"Cosmo Canyon", art:"lifestream",
    blurb:"At the canyon observatory, the elder Bugenhagen teaches the party the truth of the Lifestream — that all life flows from the Planet and returns to it. Nanaki learns that his father, Seto, died a hero defending their home.",
    detail:"Cosmo Canyon is the game's spiritual and thematic core, where Bugenhagen's planetarium spells out the Lifestream cosmology that gives every death and reactor in the story its weight. Red XIII, who believed his father Seto a coward who abandoned their tribe, is shown the truth: Seto fought Gi invaders until he was turned to stone defending the canyon, and still stands sentinel over it. It's the moment Nanaki stops being a sulky teenager and starts becoming a guardian." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"The Temple of the Ancients", spoiler:true, art:"blackmateria",
    blurb:"Under Sephiroth's mental grip, Cloud seizes the Black Materia and hands it to him, nearly killing his friends. Shaken and afraid of what he might do, Aerith slips away alone to pray for Holy.",
    detail:"The Temple of the Ancients is itself the Black Materia — to obtain the Meteor spell, the entire structure must be collapsed into a single orb, a sacrifice that costs Cait Sith his first body. The instant the Black Materia exists, Sephiroth seizes control of the Jenova-saturated Cloud, makes him pummel his own friends, and forces him to surrender the orb personally. Horrified at what he did and terrified Sephiroth will use him again, Cloud is at his lowest — and Aerith, understanding only she can stop Meteor, quietly leaves to pray for Holy alone." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"The Forgotten Capital", spoiler:true, art:"flower",
    blurb:"Aerith kneels in prayer at the City of the Ancients to summon Holy, the only counter to Meteor. As the prayer completes, Sephiroth descends and runs her through. The Planet's last Cetra returns to the Lifestream.",
    detail:"Cloud follows Aerith to the crystalline City of the Ancients, where she kneels alone on an altar, praying. In a moment of horror, the controlled Cloud nearly strikes her himself before snapping free — and then Sephiroth descends from above and impales her with the Masamune, the White Materia falling from her hand into the water below. Her death is the medium's most famous gut-punch: no revival, no resurrection arc, just sudden, permanent loss. But her prayer for Holy has already been answered; she has simply moved her struggle into the Lifestream itself." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"Cloud's True Self", spoiler:true, art:"memory",
    blurb:"Broken by Sephiroth's manipulation, Cloud collapses into the Lifestream. There Tifa helps him piece together his real memories: he was never in SOLDIER. The heroics he 'remembers' were Zack's — and Cloud finally stands as himself.",
    detail:"After handing Sephiroth the Black Materia a second time and suffering a complete breakdown, Cloud falls into the Lifestream at the Northern Crater, poisoned by Mako. Inside his own subconscious, Tifa — the one witness to the real Nibelheim — guides him through his shattered memories until he can separate Zack's life from his own. The Cloud who re-emerges isn't the invented SOLDIER hero but an ordinary man who was truly there, and accepting that is what finally lets him fight Sephiroth as himself rather than as a puppet." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"WEAPONs & the Sister Ray", spoiler:true, art:"weapon",
    blurb:"The wounded Planet spawns the colossal WEAPONs to purge the threat. Shinra turns Scarlet's giant Sister Ray cannon on the Northern Crater — and on Diamond WEAPON — as the world tips toward catastrophe.",
    detail:"As Meteor looms, the Planet awakens its monstrous WEAPONs — Diamond, Ultimate, Emerald, Ruby — to destroy any threat to its survival, humanity included. Shinra repurposes Scarlet's enormous Mako cannon, the Sister Ray, mounting it on Midgar to blast Diamond WEAPON and then the Northern Crater's barrier. The firing cracks Shinra's own HQ and seemingly kills Rufus, while the unleashed WEAPONs rampage across a world now caught between Sephiroth, Meteor, and the Planet's own immune response." },
  { era:"FFVII · Meteorfall", entry:"FFVII", yr:"Year 0", title:"Meteorfall", spoiler:true, art:"meteor",
    blurb:"Cloud's party defeats Sephiroth in the heart of the Northern Crater. As Meteor bears down on Midgar, Holy answers — and the Lifestream itself, with Aerith's guidance, surges up to push the calamity away. The Planet survives.",
    detail:"In the depths of the Northern Crater the party defeats Sephiroth's monstrous forms, and Cloud strikes down his nemesis one last time in a duel inside Cloud's own mind. But Holy, summoned by Aerith, hesitates — Meteor is already too close to Midgar. In the climax, the Lifestream itself erupts from the Planet, guided by Aerith's spirit, to hold back Meteor so Holy can finish the job. Midgar is battered but the Planet lives; five centuries later, in the ending, the land has reclaimed the ruins entirely." },

  // ---- Aftermath ----
  { era:"Aftermath", entry:"Advent Children", yr:"+2 yrs", title:"Geostigma", spoiler:true, art:"stigma",
    blurb:"Two years later, a Lifestream-borne sickness called Geostigma spreads across the world, striking down adults and children alike — a wound left in the planet's spirit by Jenova's lingering cells.",
    detail:"When the Lifestream surged up to stop Meteor, it absorbed the spiritual 'data' of Jenova's cells. Now bodies exposed to that tainted stream wage a losing war against the foreign matter, weeping black ooze — Geostigma. There is no cure. Cloud, secretly infected and consumed by guilt over Aerith and Zack, withdraws from his makeshift family, turning Advent Children into a story about whether he can forgive himself enough to keep living." },
  { era:"Aftermath", entry:"Advent Children", yr:"+2 yrs", title:"Mother's Remnants", spoiler:true, art:"remnant",
    blurb:"Three silver-haired Remnants of Sephiroth — Kadaj, Loz, and Yazoo — terrorize the children of Edge in a desperate search for the remains of 'Mother', Jenova.",
    detail:"The Remnants are Sephiroth's will, refusing to dissolve back into the Lifestream and instead coalescing into three young men — fragments of his ego, charm, and strength. Believing they need 'Mother' (Jenova's cells) to bring Sephiroth back, they manipulate the Geostigma-stricken children of Edge as a private army. They are at once menacing and pitiable: lost pieces of a dead man, searching for a parent who never existed." },
  { era:"Aftermath", entry:"Advent Children", yr:"+2 yrs", title:"One-Winged Angel, Reborn", spoiler:true, art:"stigma",
    blurb:"Kadaj absorbs Jenova's cells and becomes Sephiroth once more. Cloud defeats him in the ruins of Midgar, and a fall of rain — blessed by Aerith and the Lifestream — washes the Geostigma from the world.",
    detail:"Kadaj fuses with the box containing Jenova's remains and transforms into a fully reborn Sephiroth, who duels Cloud above the ruins of Midgar in the film's spectacular climax. Cloud, having finally chosen to live for his family rather than drown in guilt, wins — and a healing rain (the 'Great Gospel,' Aerith's gift through the Lifestream) falls over Edge, curing the Geostigma. Aerith and Zack are glimpsed one last time, at peace, watching him go." },
  { era:"Aftermath", entry:"Dirge of Cerberus", yr:"+3 yrs", title:"The Tsviets", spoiler:true, art:"deepground",
    blurb:"Deepground's elite — Weiss, Nero, Rosso, Azul, and the child-warrior Shelke — emerge from beneath the ruins of Midgar, harvesting the living to feed the Omega Project.",
    detail:"Deepground was a secret Shinra facility buried beneath Midgar, breeding soldiers in total isolation and producing the color-coded Tsviets: Weiss (white), Rosso (red), Azul (blue), Nero (black), and the Mako-frozen child Shelke. Freed by the chaos after Meteorfall, they begin abducting people en masse — fuel for a plan even most of Shinra never knew existed. Vincent, drawn out of seclusion, becomes the unlikely protagonist tasked with stopping them." },
  { era:"Aftermath", entry:"Dirge of Cerberus", yr:"+3 yrs", title:"Deepground & Omega", spoiler:true, art:"deepground",
    blurb:"Weiss rises to enact the Omega Project — gathering all Lifestream to flee a dying Planet. Vincent confronts Hojo's final scheme and his own buried past, wielding Chaos to stop Omega (Dirge of Cerberus).",
    detail:"Omega WEAPON is the Planet's ultimate failsafe: a vessel meant to gather all Lifestream and carry it off a doomed world to seed life elsewhere — leaving the husk behind. Deepground means to trigger it early, and a digitized fragment of Hojo's consciousness is pulling the strings from within the network. Vincent learns that his demon Chaos is Omega's natural counterpart, and that Shelke carries Lucrecia's memories; mastering Chaos, he stops Omega, lays his guilt over Lucrecia to rest, and — for once — chooses to keep living." },

  // ---- The Saga Continues ----
  { era:"The Saga Continues", entry:"Remake / Rebirth", yr:"reimagined", title:"Fate Unwritten", spoiler:true, art:"whisper",
    blurb:"With destiny's Whispers broken, the Remake saga walks familiar roads toward uncertain ends. Rebirth revisits the Forgotten Capital across fractured timelines, leaving the fate of beloved characters — Aerith above all — hauntingly ambiguous as the trilogy heads to its finale.",
    detail:"Freed from the Whispers, the Remake trilogy keeps the broad shape of the original while deliberately destabilizing its most sacred moments. Glimpses of a timeline where Zack survived, a Sephiroth who seems to remember the future and speak of preventing the Planet's 'end seven seconds' away, and a Forgotten Capital sequence that fractures across realities all leave Aerith's fate — and the saga's ending — genuinely uncertain for the first time in 25 years. The concluding chapter has yet to release." },
];

const COMPENDIUM = [
  /* ===== The Planet & Its Powers ===== */
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"❂", title:"The Lifestream", color:"#45e6b0",
    body:"The flow of spirit energy that courses through the Planet — the souls of all who have lived. Life springs from it and returns to it in death, carrying knowledge and memory back into the whole. To wound the Planet is to disturb this stream." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"◈", title:"Mako", color:"#45e6b0",
    body:"Lifestream refined into liquid energy. Shinra draws it through Mako reactors to power the world — but every drop burned is life stolen from the Planet, hastening its death. Prolonged exposure causes Mako poisoning." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"◉", title:"Materia", color:"#5fd0ff",
    body:"Orbs of crystallized Mako that let the wielder channel magic, summon beings, and bend the elements. They are condensed knowledge and will of the Planet itself — which is why the Cetra's wisdom sleeps within the rarest of them." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"☣", title:"Jenova", color:"#c45bff",
    body:"The 'Calamity from the Skies' — a parasitic extraterrestrial that fell ages ago and nearly annihilated the Cetra by infection and mimicry. Mistaken by Shinra for an Ancient, its cells are the thread by which Sephiroth's will spreads." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"✶", title:"The Cetra", color:"#f0c861",
    body:"The Ancients: a people who could converse with the Planet and the Lifestream, shepherding life and seeking the Promised Land. All but wiped out by Jenova, their last pure descendant is Aerith." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"✦", title:"SOLDIER", color:"#5aa6ff",
    body:"Shinra's elite warrior corps, enhanced with Mako and Jenova cells until their eyes glow. The 1st Class — Sephiroth, Genesis, Angeal, Zack — became legends, and the source of the saga's deepest tragedy." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"✵", title:"The First SOLDIER", color:"#b7e36b",
    body:"Ever Crisis's original arc, set ~15 years before FFVII. It follows the prototype 'P0' SOLDIERs — Glenn, Lucia, and Matt — and a young Sephiroth, charting the dawn of Shinra's SOLDIER program and the man Sephiroth was before his fall." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"▣", title:"Shinra Inc.", color:"#f0a830",
    body:"The megacorporation that rules the world through its monopoly on Mako energy. Equal parts government, military, and science cult, it treats the Planet's lifeblood as a balance sheet — making it the engine of every catastrophe to follow." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"▲", title:"The WEAPONs", color:"#e2576b",
    body:"Titanic living guardians created by the Planet as a last line of defense, awakened when its survival is threatened. Emerald, Ruby, Diamond and their kin strike indiscriminately at any sufficient threat — including humanity." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"❖", title:"The Promised Land", color:"#f0c861",
    body:"A fabled land of supreme happiness, said to overflow with Mako. The Cetra sought it as a reward; Shinra coveted it as the ultimate energy source; Sephiroth means to claim it as a god. What it truly is remains a matter of faith." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"⚕", title:"Geostigma", color:"#9a6bff",
    body:"A lethal plague that follows Meteorfall: the body, exposed to Lifestream tainted by Jenova's cells, wages war on the foreign matter and poisons itself. A wound in the Planet's spirit, ultimately healed by Aerith's blessing (Advent Children)." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"⬢", title:"Deepground", color:"#c45bff",
    body:"A secret Shinra army bred in the tunnels beneath Midgar, its elite 'Tsviets' enhanced beyond even SOLDIER. Unleashed in Dirge of Cerberus, they seek to awaken Omega WEAPON and carry the Lifestream off a dying world." },
  { cat:"The Planet & Its Powers", sigil:"≋", title:"The Whispers", color:"#5fd0ff",
    body:"Spectral 'Arbiters of Fate' introduced in Remake: ghostly guardians that force events back onto destiny's known path whenever the story strays. Defeating them is a literal break with the original — the device that lets the Remake saga diverge." },

  /* ===== Summons ===== */
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"✺", title:"Summon Materia", color:"#e85b6b",
    body:"Rare red Materia that call a mighty being to the battlefield for a single, devastating intervention. In FFVII they bind gods and monsters into crystal; in Remake and Rebirth they are manifestations of the Planet's memory, earned by proving yourself against them in Chadley's combat simulations." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"✸", title:"Ifrit", color:"#f0782a",
    body:"A horned demon wreathed in hellfire, one of the first summons most travellers bind. He answers with Hellfire, scorching every foe on the field." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"❄", title:"Shiva", color:"#7fd6ff",
    body:"An elegant spirit of ice who descends to sheathe the battlefield in killing frost — her Diamond Dust freezing enemies where they stand." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"⚡", title:"Ramuh", color:"#f0c861",
    body:"A staff-bearing elder sage of storms who passes sentence with a single Judgment Bolt, calling lightning down upon all who oppose his summoner." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"◆", title:"Titan", color:"#b9894a",
    body:"A mountainous giant of earth who heaves the very ground skyward — Anger of the Land — crushing everything standing upon it." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"≋", title:"Leviathan", color:"#45b6e6",
    body:"A colossal sea serpent revered as a guardian deity in Wutai, who drowns the battlefield beneath a towering tidal wave." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"⚔", title:"Odin", color:"#b9c3c9",
    body:"A spectral knight astride the steed Sleipnir. He decapitates lesser foes outright with Zantetsuken, or impales the mighty on the Gungnir lance." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"✦", title:"Bahamut", color:"#c45bff",
    body:"The King of Dragons, who razes all before him with Mega Flare. FFVII hides three escalating forms — Bahamut, Neo Bahamut, and the planet-scouring Bahamut ZERO." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"✚", title:"Alexander", color:"#cfd8d4",
    body:"A colossal walking citadel of holy light whose Divine Judgment rains down on the unrighteous — one of the rare summons of the Holy element." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"✷", title:"Phoenix", color:"#ff7a3a",
    body:"A blazing firebird whose Rebirth Flame scorches the enemy and resurrects the fallen — the Lifestream's promise made manifest: death feeds new life." },
  { cat:"Summons", sigil:"♛", title:"Knights of the Round", color:"#f0c861",
    body:"The ultimate summon: thirteen Knights of the Round Table who each strike in turn for an 'Ultimate End.' It is hidden behind one of FFVII's most demanding quests — breeding a Gold Chocobo to reach a lone hidden island." },

  /* ===== Artifacts & Weapons ===== */
  { cat:"Artifacts & Weapons", sigil:"†", title:"The Buster Sword", color:"#8fb4c0",
    body:"Angeal Hewley's massive broadsword, kept pristine as the symbol of 'honor and dreams.' It passes from Angeal to Zack to Cloud — the heirloom that binds all three swordsmen — and stands as Zack's grave marker on the cliffs above Midgar." },
  { cat:"Artifacts & Weapons", sigil:"✛", title:"The Masamune", color:"#c45bff",
    body:"Sephiroth's impossibly long nodachi, named for the legendary real-world swordsmith Masamune. Its reach lets him strike from beyond any guard — and it is the blade that slays both President Shinra and Aerith." },
  { cat:"Artifacts & Weapons", sigil:"⚔", title:"The Fusion Swords", color:"#b9c3c9",
    body:"Cloud's six-piece modular sword in Advent Children: separate blades that lock into one and can be drawn apart mid-fight. An evolution of the Buster Sword, and a monument to every blade — and friend — he carries." },
  { cat:"Artifacts & Weapons", sigil:"◐", title:"Black & White Materia", color:"#cfd8d4",
    body:"The two ultimate magics. The Black Materia casts Meteor, summoning a falling star to gouge the Planet — Sephiroth's chosen weapon. The White Materia casts Holy, the Planet's ultimate protection, which only a Cetra can call." },
  { cat:"Artifacts & Weapons", sigil:"⬟", title:"The Keystone", color:"#d8b48c",
    body:"The relic that unlocks the Temple of the Ancients. Cait Sith — under Shinra's orders — hands it to the Turks, a betrayal that lets Sephiroth close in on the Black Materia." },
  { cat:"Artifacts & Weapons", sigil:"◉", title:"Huge Materia", color:"#45e6b0",
    body:"Four enormous Materia of immense condensed energy, the distilled output of Shinra's reactors. Shinra means to fire them into Meteor; the party races by train, rocket, and submarine to seize them first." },
  { cat:"Artifacts & Weapons", sigil:"⬡", title:"The Protomateria", color:"#9a6bff",
    body:"A rare Materia that lets its bearer command the demon Chaos. Stolen from Vincent and central to Dirge of Cerberus, it is the key to controlling — or unleashing — Omega WEAPON." },
];
